\@writefile{lof}{\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {2}{\ignorespaces \textbf  {Path Opacity and the Monotone Record: An Agent Cannot Reconstruct the Route to Its Own Account.} (\textbf  {A})~Distinct interiors between the same endpoints on the linear $y$-axis versus world density on the linear $x$-axis ($0.3$ to $0.95$) (steel-blue), with the single-interior line marked (crimson, dashed). The count of distinct routes to one terminus rises above one as density grows, the empirical content of \Cref  {thm:opacity}(i): same-endpoint searches generically differ in interior. (\textbf  {B})~Number of searches on the linear $y$-axis versus interior length for a fixed seed and terminus on the linear $x$-axis (sea-green). Many interior lengths reach the same endpoints, the empirical content of \Cref  {thm:opacity}(ii): the report does not determine the interior. (\textbf  {C})~Three-dimensional bundle of up to four same-endpoint search walks, items placed on a ring in $(x,y)$ with search step on the $z$-axis (steel-blue, sea-green, amber, violet) from the common seed (crimson), viewing angle elevation $22^{\circ }$ azimuth $-60^{\circ }$. The walks share endpoints but trace different interiors, the geometric picture of path opacity. (\textbf  {D})~Position on the linear $y$-axis versus the strictly increasing committed record $M$ on the linear $x$-axis ($1$ to $45$), points coloured by record (plasma), with the revisits of the initial position ringed (crimson). A position recurs but the record never returns, the empirical content of \Cref  {cor:noreconstruct}: the committed record is monotone and the interior is a past state the agent does not re-occupy.}}{8}{figure.caption.3}\protected@file@percent }
\newlabel{fig:mechanics-2}{{2}{8}{\textbf {Path Opacity and the Monotone Record: An Agent Cannot Reconstruct the Route to Its Own Account.} (\textbf {A})~Distinct interiors between the same endpoints on the linear $y$-axis versus world density on the linear $x$-axis ($0.3$ to $0.95$) (steel-blue), with the single-interior line marked (crimson, dashed). The count of distinct routes to one terminus rises above one as density grows, the empirical content of \Cref {thm:opacity}(i): same-endpoint searches generically differ in interior. (\textbf {B})~Number of searches on the linear $y$-axis versus interior length for a fixed seed and terminus on the linear $x$-axis (sea-green). Many interior lengths reach the same endpoints, the empirical content of \Cref {thm:opacity}(ii): the report does not determine the interior. (\textbf {C})~Three-dimensional bundle of up to four same-endpoint search walks, items placed on a ring in $(x,y)$ with search step on the $z$-axis (steel-blue, sea-green, amber, violet) from the common seed (crimson), viewing angle elevation $22^{\circ }$ azimuth $-60^{\circ }$. The walks share endpoints but trace different interiors, the geometric picture of path opacity. (\textbf {D})~Position on the linear $y$-axis versus the strictly increasing committed record $M$ on the linear $x$-axis ($1$ to $45$), points coloured by record (plasma), with the revisits of the initial position ringed (crimson). A position recurs but the record never returns, the empirical content of \Cref {cor:noreconstruct}: the committed record is monotone and the interior is a past state the agent does not re-occupy}{figure.caption.3}{}}
\newlabel{fig:mechanics-2@cref}{{[figure][2][]2}{[1][7][]8}{}{}{}}
